"Only when cython does python 3 support. \n\n> On Aug 16, 2014, at 4:22 PM, iRaffnix notifications@github.com wrote:\n> \n> Dear all!\n> \n> unfortunately iminuit is not Python3 compatible.\n> Is it planned to overcome this little problem in the future?\n> \n> Cheers,\n> iRaffnix\n> \n> \u2014\n> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub.\n\n\nDoesn't Cython do python 3 support? https://github.com/cython/cython/wiki/FAQ#id13\n\n\n@rknegjens Yes, Python 3 support shouldn't be too hard.\nI'll give it a try next weekend.\n\n\nNice....\nAm 03.11.2014 09:42 schrieb \"Christoph Deil\" notifications@github.com:\n\n> @rknegjens https://github.com/rknegjens Yes, Python 3 support shouldn't\n> be too hard.\n> I'll give it a try next weekend.\n> \n> \u2014\n> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub\n> https://github.com/iminuit/iminuit/issues/123#issuecomment-61450954.\n\n\nMy Vague recollection tells you will need to do a lot of things to describe to get it to work with python3. Extracting information from a function works a bit differently there.\n\n\n@cdeil did you make any progress on this? I'm in the midst of implementing py3 support in sncosmo but realized that this is a key missing dependency for us.\n\n\nI did start but then couldn't figure out something in https://github.com/iminuit/iminuit/blob/master/iminuit/util.py .\n\nIf you know Py 2 / 3 it should be pretty easy (try to get all tests to pass, use 2to3 for guidance) ... I'm just not very good at it.\n\n@kbarbary - If you don't have time for this, I'll have another look on Monday.\n\n\nWas there something specific in util?\n\nDoes the build use the 2to3 tool? (Is that done automatically in `setup()` if you don't specify it?)\n\n\nI started to work on this, but ran into some trouble compiling. On my platform (ubuntu 14.04), distutils wants to use the executable `g++44` to create the shared library. It's not installed. I have `g++` installed (v4.8.x). I can't figure out why distutis insists on calling `g++44`. Any ideas, linux users?\n\n\n@kbarbary - Thanks for trying to make Python 3 work.\n\nHere's what `2to3` does to `iminuit/util.py`:\nhttps://gist.github.com/cdeil/c264e24dd22ae2c97a1a\n\nInstead we should find a way to re-write it to have a codebase that simultaneously works with Python 2 and 3 ... if possibly confining the Python 2 / 3 differences into [iminuit/py23_compat.py](https://github.com/iminuit/iminuit/blob/master/iminuit/py23_compat.py).\n\nNo idea why the build tries to use  `g++44` for linking ... maybe if you copy & paste the full log into a gist I can spot something ... \n\n\nIs there some reason not to use six? I thought that was the favored approach over the monkeypatching that python-future does.\n\nThere's really not any useful info in the output I'm getting. It calls `gcc` to compile everything, with warnings issued from `cc1plus` and then calls `g++44` in the final linking step.\n\n\nThe root of my compilation problem:\n\n```\nIn [6]: from distutils import sysconfig\n\nIn [7]: sysconfig.get_config_var(\"CXX\")\nOut[7]: 'g++44 -pthread'\n```\n\nBut why...? Anyway, this is off-topic for this issue. Sorry about that. \n\n\nUsing `six` would be fine.\n\n\nOther function should work fine but you will need to edit describe manually though. The fubction signature is at different place i think. \n\n> On Dec 29, 2014, at 7:02 AM, Christoph Deil notifications@github.com wrote:\n> \n> Using six would be fine.\n> \n> \u2014\n> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub.\n\n\nHi, has there been any movement on this issue? Python 3 support for iminuit would be fantastic.\n\n\nOkie. I'll investigate this for real this time.\n"